Go big with the left hand, cut feet for style points, and bring your right hand over to match the flake. Finish with a big and easy toss up to the the big ledge directly above the flake, or finish on the Rainbow.The big jug ledge near the end of the crack is off.

Location: The Danger Dam > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: This problem is only 3 moves, but they are pretty fun ones. Stand start on two parallel holds below the end of Lushes Lip, and climb the face to the right of the arete, using a gaston and nice sculpted sidepull. Finish by matching the top of Rich's Arete.

Location: The Danger Dam > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Fun variation of Iron Cross. Start on the same big ledge and make the same initial moves as Iron Cross, but once you are situated in the pocket, move up into the crimp and make a toss for the big ledge directly above you. Finish on Poison Ivy (traverse the ledge right, into the finishing jug for The Rainbow).

Location: The Danger Dam > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with hands on the big chalked-up ledge. Move right into the crimpy pocket and execute the iron cross into the juggy left-facing flake (the higher crimp between the pocket and flake is off). Finish on The Rainbow.

Location: The Danger Dam > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start at the base of the crack and climb it until it peters out (juggy ledges to the left of the crack are off). Move up to a good sloping pocket and then to a sharp crimp pocket above it. Make a big move with the right hand to the small but positive gaston, then fire up for a crimp just below the lip. Finish on the juggy lip.There are three variations/eliminates for this problem; here is abeta videofrom Rich showing which holds are on.

Location: The Danger Dam > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the two obvious crimps moving left horizontal to the two other crimps. Finding good footing to start is good for right foot, but suspect for the left foot.Throw left hand up to mini jug and work your way up to large jug that's left and up. Find some feet then head up and right to crimps then a far right to ledge (crux is these last few moves mentioned). From there top out with by throwing a heal up and moving a little further to the left and over. If you don't go over the top no worries, has lots of vegetation so can be muddy and slippery.Contrived problem, but some good heal hooks and crux at the end. Most problems are easy on this wall, but a pretty decent one for the area. This may already be a problem, but because of all the "not in plays" it may not have been.

Location: Council Rock > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with large jugs on the far left. Traverse right using the lowest holds and exit right onto the lower ledge.

Location: Council Rock > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the obvious hold on the lower left. Climb the nice holds to the left of the arÃªte.

Location: Council Rock > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on large jugs on the left and traverse up and right across the face. Climb up on jugs on the right side of the face and top out over the highest point.

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the huge jug at the base. Boulder at the base is on. Throw straight up to the lip and top out. Far right jugs and arÃªte are off.Beta Vid

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start with a left heel, reach up to the crack and move right. Solid top out.Beta Vid

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with a hand on the lip and a hand in the tiny but incut crimp under the lip. Make a hard starting move to a juggy flake and then follow jugs up and right.

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start on a jug and work up and right on good holds. Figure out a way to reach the crack on the face above the roof, and then manage the scary and insecure topout. A key hold on the lip is hollow sounding and flexing, might break off after another winter freeze/thaw.

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on jug below the boulder. Move on ledge right until top out. Do not use the detached block for feet.

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start with hands on the slopey start and toes hooked around the arete as seen in the picture. Move up and top out over the lip. Make sure to have a spotter as a fall could send you tumbling down the hill.Beta Video:

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: I believe this is a FA. start with left hand on crimp, and right hand on the obvious hold. Go directly up and over the bulge of the boulder to top out.Beta Vid:

Route: A Very Good Cool Down Problem
Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start at the base of Ben Franklin and moves up and right to the obvious positive (and very sharp) horizontal. Follow the progressively smoother and smaller holds moving right to the obvious finish rail. Nice traverse for waiting out the rain.

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the jug below boulder and move straight up the face. Do NOT use the block.

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: It's an eliminate, but hey, this is the Wiss. Sit start with hands on the sloping rail at the right end of the boulder. Move left, through textured slopers and the perpetually-soggy crimps and into the big jug underneath the "dirty dishes" holds, without using the dishes. Keep traversing left to the big sharp jug on the arete, or save yourself the pump and shoot directly to the good holds above the jug on the arete. Top out as for Ben Franklin.

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: V4- Version: Sit start on crimps in center face. Move up to a jug then work up and right to a large slot without using the jugs out left. Top out above.V3+ Version: Sit start on crimps in center face. Move up using your choice of holds and top out.

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start as for Dirty Dishes [V3] and bust right using some awkward body tension cross moves. Finish as for I'm Bringing Lobsterbacks [V2].

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start with hands on the sloping rail at the right end of the boulder. Make your way left to the "dirty dishes" holds and keep going (crux) until you hit the arete. Top out as for Ben Franklin.

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the jug at the base. Boulder at the base is on. Throw a right heel and move left on frictiony holds. Use the arete and crimps to get up and top out.Beta Video

Location: Revolutionary Ridge Boulders > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the jug under the boulder. Toe hook to start, the kick boulder is off. Bump to a good right hand and kick around to a hand foot match with a right heel. (Hard not to dab)Use slopers to get to the Arete, then make a match on a wide pinch. Exit out to left of the Arete and start hold. Mellow topout

Location: Wissahickon Hermit Boulder > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start your way up by using the first obvious sloper. Work your way up by using the small finger slots or the other slopers.The climb is finished at the very last hold.

Location: Devil's Pool Boulder > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb the arete on the far right of the boulder up to the alcove, and follow up to the top.

Location: Devil's Pool Boulder > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with hand jams as low as possible in the lower left of the diagonally running hand crack. Follow the crack up and right where it flares out. The crux is getting from the flare to the upper lip of the boulder and there are two ways to go about it. Either make a reachy dynamic throw to the lip, or calf hook into the flare and use an undercling to wrestle your way into an insecure heel/toe cam then reach for the lip. Either method is very committing and having a spotter would be very nice psychological pro. The topout is easy enough but not a "gimme" so exercise caution as it would be a nasty fall coming off of the top.

Location: Devil's Pool Boulder > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the juggy left crack and climb straight up

Location: Devil's Pool Boulder > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Starting on the far right of the front face, traverse left to the sloping crack until you reach the start of "Unknown Herb", Finish on "Unknown Herb".

Location: Devil's Pool Boulder > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start in the prominent crack that "Wrastlin'" follows, but climb straight up the face and out left.

Location: Gorgas Creek Cave > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on right side of lower rock formation and traverse left along obvious upper jug. Â Lower crack provides secure feet. Â Top out is slightly around the left side but be aware some rocks may be loose.

Location: Gorgas Creek Cave > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start using the lower crack with sloping handholds. Â Lay back and find foot holds inside the cave. Â Traverse the cave opening by swiveling your hips to find footholds on lower left side of cave wall. Â Proceed to obvious top out.

Location: Gorgas Creek Cave > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start where the left side of the cave meets the ground, not in the cave but on the outside as it begins to wrap around the corner. Traverse right over the opening of the cave. At some point you'll need to switch feet from one side to the other while your hands are towards the center of the top of the "rainbow" arch. Continue the traverse until you're fully to the right of the arch, then follow the crack up to the top edge of the rock (top rock is a bit dirty / overgrown), and follow that edge back over the cave until you're fully wrapped around the left side of the rock formation.

Location: Gorgas Creek Cave > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start inside the cave about 4 ft in to the right. Two hand start on most obvious overhanging hold (it's well chalked). Â Continue out to the lower right area of cave entrance and stay low with hands while moving to the lower left of cave entrance. My finish was a prominent hold to the left of entrance where I could firmly place two hands with relatively good footing. There is also an obvious top out variation that's still in the V3-category.

Location: The Peak Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS on the face to the left of the cave with a small left edge and large right jug. Climb straight up and top out in the space next to the tree.

Location: The Peak Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start low in the shallow cave and move up and right along a system of jugs. Top out over the lower ledge on the right side of the face. The difficulty level will probably depend mostly on how deep in the cave you begin.

Location: The Peak Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Right in between the rifle and the long lady. This time you are sending it all the way too the top. Have plenty of pads and spotters!

Location: The Cubicle Area > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS as low as possible with your choice of great holds. Move up over the bulge and top out. Great warm out.

Location: The Cubicle Area > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the lower crack and move up/across the overhang and top out on the right side. Side rock is on for V0, but can make it more challenging by skipping that feature. Avoid the dirt on the right!

Location: The Cubicle Area > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Begin on crimps on the slab at the base. Move up between the two walls and top out.

Location: The Thorny Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start with feet swept out to the left. Low crimpy holds and a heel hook may be useful beta. Make 1 or 2 powerful moves (height dependent) up to the contoured pocket and jug on the right. Match feet in the pocket and proceed to top out.

Location: The Thorny Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the far left and traverse right as far as possible before topping out. The top ledge is on.

Location: The Thorny Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS with crimps at the bottom left. Move up on a sloper to a horizontal crack midway up. Keep moving and top out. Most holds are pretty clear of lichen already but you may have to brush a few holds.Beta Video

Location: The Thorny Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS matched on the sharp arete in the middle of the wall. Move up to friendlier jugs in a crack on the right. Top out above.Beta Video

Location: The Thorny Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start on a jug flake below the blunt arete. Climb up and right following a large slanting crack to the top.

Location: The Thorny Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start with hands matched on half moon crimp. Left foot heel hook, far right reach to knobby jub. Continue to contoured shelf and easy top out diagonally right.

Location: The Thorny Boulder > Valley Green > Wissahickon Valley Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania

Description: Start with a large jug and high feet over the water's edge. Throw to good holds along the top of the boulder. There are plenty of foot options for those who like to smear or throw in heel and toe hooks. Once both hands are on the main horizontal crack in the boulder, throwing the right hand to a high sharp crimp will be the crux. Tall climbers will be able to skip this intermediate crimp and should throw their right hand in to a slightly farther jug just past the crimp. Rock over the high right foot and reach up to the last two top out jugs to stand up.

Route: Ten Thousand Feet Up Mega Traverse
Location: Ten Thousand Feet Up Area > Lorimer Park > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: There are many ways to play on this wall but we do one very long traverse that keeps you low, eliminating the need for crash pads. This route begins V-easy and ends V-hard (but I usually climb with ropes so I'm not that familiar with bouldering grades. Open to suggestions.) Start standing on a coffee table size rock. Pretend you are standing on a ledge ten thousand feet up. Proceed through the easy Orangutan/Jungle Traverse, which is an excellent warm-up. Stem through the dihedral. Throw a calf up and around the corner and step up high to keep things easy or stay low around the corner for a challenge. Down-climb or stay low to continue traversing through some wide reaches until reaching another good resting spot. Breeze through a long easy section and then take a rest before the cave. Continue into the cave, being aware of the sharp boulder under your back. Climb up and out of the cave to the right, watching for loose blocks. Try to gain a comfortable stance and rest as if you are ten thousand feet up until you are ready to do it all in reverse!

Location: Quarantine Boulders > Cobbs Creek > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Stand start on the far right of the lip with a right jug and a left sloper. Traverse left across the lip and around the corner. Top out same as Happy Birthday Arete.

Location: Wall Park Boulder > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: The easiest/simplest climb on the boulder. Share a start with Pinchy and link into Crimps N Slots. Head straight up for the first ledge and topout.

Location: Wall Park Boulder > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Traverse left through slots until arete and then make move straight up, topping out on the first ledge. (Not Marco Polo topout)

Location: Wall Park Boulder > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start the same as "The Direct", low and left, and make moves to a right handed pinch. The first ledge is OFF ("The Direct" topout). Instead reach far for a crimp below the second ledge. Proceed to the top with other holds.

Location: Wall Park Boulder > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Probably has the nicest movement on the boulder. Move through cracks, sidepulls and slopers to the top.

Location: Wall Park Boulder > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: The tallest line on the boulder which gets a bit scary because you feel like you're over a rock. For the full value line, start on "The Direct" and traverse right into the start.

Location: Yorktown Plaza > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Crux is early on again. The landing on this one isn't great with a big tree stump in the way. Spotter would be nice. Move onto the arete and maybe sneak a right heel hook on the start hold to move to better holds.

Location: Yorktown Plaza > Philly > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: First move is crux. Dyno with bad feet to a good sloper. This move could be harder than V4 but once you stick it, the climb is just about over. Climb through one more reachy move after the dyno to jugs.

Location: Downingtown Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: The problem is a fun warm up to do. It is a crack with some pretty chunky holds on it.

Location: Downingtown Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on an undercling and side pull. Reach for the lip and top out.

Location: Downingtown Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: You start with two wide underclings to get up onto the slab, which is the crux. Then climb the sob to the top

Location: Downingtown Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start on a crimp and pocket and make a big move to a jug and top out.

Location: Downingtown Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sharp crimps and some flakes at the top, topout is the crux.

Location: Downingtown Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: The start of the problem is on the lower right hand corner of the boulder. Then you traverse to where the boulder and the tree meet, then you top out.

Location: Downingtown Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start in the middle of the same boulder as Business Time on two crimps. Move up to a flake and traverse left to the same top out as Business Time.

Location: Ridley Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: This problem is found on the main boulder on the right side. The side resembles a heart. It is a simple crack problem. Its a short crack climb that starts with right foot out on a small rock in the ground and then a wide left foot on the base of the main boulder. Start with hands in the crack then cross hands up further on the crack and then bring right foot over to left foot and back flag the left. Move up the crack crossing hands and then pull up on top of boulder to top out.

Location: Ridley Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with a hang start with feet on small rock under the first ledge. Cross left hand to small crimp swing out to grab a crimp on the other side of the ledge with right hand. While hanging throw a heel hook with right foot while flagging with left. Crank up and grab the point of the second ledge. Step up and top out.

Location: Ridley Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: This problem starts with two feet on a smaller rock and two hands low on the first part of the boulder. Cross with your right hand further up on the same part you started on and then match hands. Throw a heel hook with your left foot to the edge. Put your right foot up onto the second part of the boulder and push up to grab with your right hand to the top part of the second part of the boulder and match hands. Then work your way up to the top using the edge of the boulder for feet. Top out.

Location: Ridley Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Its a shorter problem if you have a crash pad bring it!

Location: Warm up boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb the slab face next to the roof on the left.

Location: Warm up boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb the slab face. watch for loose pebbles.

Location: Warm up boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: stem your way up the crack in corner.

Location: Warm up boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Step out on the ledge and climb the face

Location: Warm up boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the corner and make your way up  on the left side of the face

Location: Warm up boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb the arÃªte.

Location: Warm up boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb the crack

Location: Warm up boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: crux is the start. climb up into the roof. pull roof on right side of the arÃªte and finish up the slab.

Location: Warm up boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb the left side of the face on the arÃªte.

Location: Solo Boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with your feet under the lower roof with your hand on the first good hold. work your way up the face and mantel on the rock above

Location: Lower Boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: start low on the slab move up and left over the roof to a hard mantel

Location: The Gem > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with your hands on the dish in the lower middle of the boulder and climb left working your way to the point at the end of the boulder. a fun sustained problem with great moves. the crux is where ever your anaerobic respiration kicks in.

Location: The Gem > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: FA: kyle stromanThis is the sit variation of working man, it adds an additional 3 moves. Start on two crimps a few feet right of the dish and throw a heel hook, cross right hand over to another crimp. Reach left hand out for the dish and lock in your core to match. Finish the rest of the boulder as you would for working man.You could start even further to the right if you want, but starting here prevents the annoying butt dab.

Location: Cobra rock > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the right side of the rock with an under cling reach for the crack. Crux is the first move into the crack

Location: Cobra rock > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start in the crack on the left side and traverse right and mantle on the right side of the rock.

Location: Cobra rock > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the cobra hood with a compression hold, and move straight up. Rock on the left is off.

Location: High Ball Boulder > Hay Creek Boulders > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the right side of the south face of the boulder. make a few moves then make a small traverse left and continue straight up the boulder.

Location: Chester Valley Trail Outcrop > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with a right hand undercling and obvious right foot, left hand in undercling in the crack. Work up the flake to your left, move right then top out.

Location: Chester Valley Trail Outcrop > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Lots of ways to go about this one. Sit start under the fat crack and work your way up. Its wide enugh to be hand jammed but featured enough that it really isn't necessary.

Location: The Bunker > Saint Peter's Village > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on good but small hands on the ledge below the crack, left foot smear and right foot on a small edge. Use the flaring crack to work hands up and then feet. This is a good problem for someone looking to get practice with different crack sizes. Although the crack is short if so inclined you could get 6-7 jams in before topping out (I did it in 3, a finger, hand, and fist jam)

Location: The Bunker > Saint Peter's Village > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with feet on large angling boulder on the right end of the cave and hands on underclings of the top boulder. Work feet up the bottom and hands up the top until you can bump out left and let feet loose. Get a heel hook on the lip and make a scary mantle then scramble the slabby featured face to top out.

Route: Whoever Killed That Tree Your Moms A Hoe
Location: The Bunker > Saint Peter's Village > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start low and let on the end of the crescent shaped crack on incut small holds, feet on the base of boulder on good feet. Bump hands right along shallow crack (watch out for the corpse of the baby tree growing in the crack) and adjust feet on base. Either follow thinning fingertip sidepulls up the crack and an arduous high right foot to top out, or get yourself set on a good right hand and lunge up with the left for a sloper, heel hook and top out. Both ways are difficult, maybe v3. Please be careful to not lay your pad in such a way that you will stress the small tree at the back of the landing.

Location: Clearcoat Face > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb up the left side of the clearoat face. Big chunky holds lead to a sloped topout. Topout probably the crux.

Location: Clearcoat Face > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Stand start with a hand on a big crimp/edge and one on the separated but still solid small block in the seam. Â Work up on good feet and hands to a juggy edge shrouded in ferns: this is the commitment point. Work some slightly high feet up (you better trust them) and make a reachy move up over the next block to another juggy edge, and then repeat that sequence to the final jutting out edge. Walk off the slabby topout of clearcoat face to the left. Careful, that topout slab is more slippery than it looks.

Location: Clearcoat Face > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Contrived sit start that shares a finish with "Clearcoat Arete". Start with hands on large triangular ledge and high feet. Work up and left on small but mostly positive edges and top out near the arete.

Location: Clearcoat Face > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Tiny negative holds until you hit the crack, and then they're still tiny. Be careful as you tend to lean right near the top and a fall could be very very bad if not protected right.

Location: Clearcoat Face > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: The best climbing in the clearcoat area, but by far the worst landing. Start with hands in chunky opening on the left face. Swing/slap up to an edge around the right side of the face. Heel hook wide right to allow you to pinch the polished arete and then bump your right hand to a bad 2 finger uncut edge. Open those hips and get a high foot to stand up.

Location: Clearcoat Face > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start matched on the large ledge that is the left hand start of Clearcoat Arete. Keep to the right of the crack. Do 3 or 4 small moves up small negative crimps and gun it for the top. Top move is scary, and may be harder for smaller climbers.

Location: Peace Pipe > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start low with hands matched on the obvious rail, pull up and get the right hand in the undercling, then match (I've tried many many times but it only goes if you match). Bump both hands up to the flake, and then campus or traverse left. topout where the ledge ends.

Location: Peace Pipe > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Same Start as peace pipe, but mantel directly up over the top. The mantel move is on good holds however the ledge that you exit onto is small (about a foot and a half wide) and typically overgrown with ferns if not recently cleaned off. Would be an unpleasant fall if not committed to the move completely.

Location: Protection Face > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start with your hands on the big flake and your feet in the crack. Move to the obvious side pull and then match on the rail above it. The rest is pretty much all small rough crimps until you get to the big edge just below the top. The crux is getting your left hand in up into a tiny negative crack thing without peeling off the wall. very fun problem once you work that out.

Location: Protection Face > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Just an extension to heebee jeebees starting out to the left. Really no harder, just a little more pump.

Location: Baby Roof > Whittaker Trail Head Memorial Park > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with hands spread wide in compression across the bottom corners of the overhanging block, get creative with feet. Bump the left hand up to a finger wide flare in the crack, and then either find a way to bump right hand to crimpy edges, or establish good feet and throw with the left for the top, and then head up and right to top out.

Location: Shelmire Road Hillside > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start up that the horizontal crack in the featured concave slabby rock. Trust your feet to smearing and work your way up the well featured face.

Location: Shelmire Road Hillside > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb the featured slab left of Breakfast at Cliffany's

Location: Shelmire Road Hillside > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on a small left facing flake at about chest height work up on good crimps and small edges into a corner dihedralish feature. Top out and walk off. Tall and scarier than it is difficult. Really good quality rock, not sure what it is though.

Location: Shelmire Road Hillside > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with hands in the large left facing flake to the right of "Tripping While Dogsitting" and with good feet. Layback up and get some crimps to pull over the bulge. The crack is home to a myriad of spiders in the warm months.

Location: Shelmire Road Hillside > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start matching the large sidepull flake and move up to the left hand crimp. Afterwards move up to a solid righthand crimp before throwing to the top lip.A much easier version of this line is possible by using the large crack between the last crimp and the top, but it was much less fun.

Location: Shelmire Road Hillside > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start as for "Breakfast at Cliffany's" on the left facing flake. Bump up and right to a far gaston, adjust feet and reach for the arching crimp rail above the gaston. Match the arching crimp rail and follow mossy slightly incut edges up over the bulge.

Location: Shelmire Road Hillside > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start with hands in flake and feet far left. Pull up to two good edges, find feet, and then pull up to a right hand on your choice of a glassy crimp, a tiny bad Gaston pocket, or a bad slope. Set feet and then launch for the jugs above the bulge. Try not to dry fire off the glassy crimp, it hurts.

Location: N Reeds Road Hollow > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start at the small gully in the rock just left of the cutout corner. Work up the face on easy smearing and dirty jugs.

Location: N Reeds Road Hollow > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start as for "Negative Space" But move straight up from the start

Location: N Reeds Road Hollow > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start matched on an incut section on the left side of the lip above the cutout, feet on the overhanging section under the cutout (small wall to the right is off). Bump hands up and right to good hold, get a left foot above the lip and find holds to stand up on it. Finish by topping out a slightly delicate slab with decent holds if you look for them. Rock seemed solid but the edges of some holds on the bottom may crumble and round as it cleans up. Fun movement, goes at V0-1 if you use feet or hands on the right wall to start.

Location: N Reeds Road Hollow > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start matched on the left side of the cutout corner around the left side of the overhanging face. Move to the right wall of the corner and reach for the lip. Manage less than ideal hands and feet you cant see to move yourself up. Awkward exposed move up over the lip.

Location: N Reeds Road Hollow > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on any of a selection of good holds on the lip of the overhanging face far left. Follow good holds traversing right along the lip with small feet on the overhanging faceuntil you need to throw for the broken corner jug and let feet come loose. Get a hand heel match and mantel, top out.

Location: N Reeds Road Hollow > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with wide hands on incut but small holds, small smeary feet. Press hard with the feet and bump a hand up high, then another bump for the other hand. Hard to describe beta. This thing is stiff.

Location: Marsh Creek Lake Drainage Area > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb the arete to top-out.

Location: Marsh Creek Lake Drainage Area > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Climb the tall featured face, not all that exciting but its something.

Location: Marsh Creek Lake Drainage Area > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Sit start with hands on slopey rail. Move up and left to a really nice pocket. Match the side-pull above it and move right to small crimps. Find balance and move up to incut jugs for top out. Arete on right side of boulder is off.

Location: Controlled Descent Boulder > Mount Johnson Nature Center Overhangs > East Branch Brandywine Creek > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start low on positive crimps and then work your way up on small positive holds and top out, many ways about it all about the same difficulty.

Location: The Falls > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start scrunched up with hands matched on the right side of the "boulder." After a few moves traversing to the left, topout.

Location: The Falls > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start low on the right side of the boulder, and follow the line up and to the left. The top out can be tricky.

Location: The Falls > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Probably one of the best problems I've ever done. Start in the very bottom of the cave with a left hand undercling and a slopey right hand. Follow the line of good holds up and to the left.

Location: The Falls > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: The problem follows the rightmost arete of the cave, starting with both hands as low as you can go. Luckily, these holds tend to remain dry when the rest of the cave is still soaked.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start somewhere on the right side of the boulder, and head up and to a little to the left before topping out.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on any of the numerous juggy holds on the left side, and go up and to the right for the topout.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Super cool feature. This boulder is a thin flake of black rock with big jugs, making it a Â good warmup.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with hands as shown in the picture or wherever there are dry holds, and head up and to the right quite aways before topping out.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with both hands matched on the basketball sized ball. You can go up either left or right, either way it's juggy slab climbing.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start low on the right side of the outcropping with hands as shown in the picture. Head up and over the bloc containing the start holds for the topout.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Low start at the left end of the steep overhang on a high right hand pinch and a low sloper left hand, climbing all the way out under the tree to the right.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start towards the left side of the outcropping, with hands as shown in the pictures. Avoiding the detached bloc below to the right of the start, go up and to the right for the top out.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: This climb starts by sitting down against the tree at the far left, matched on a good jug. Continue climbing the arete (using the holds on the roof too) all the way around to the right end. I didn't top it out because it was raining, but it's probably possible.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS with both hands matched on a slopey sidepull. Go up and to the left for a few moves before topping out.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: This climb starts with a high left hand and lower right hand inside the cave. Follow the arete and avoid dabbing since it's so low, finishing matched on the hold at the far right end.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with both hands matched on the leftmost jug. Climb a few moderately difficult moves into the starting position of Gengar.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start matched on a crimp rail on the lower detached bloc. After some delicate moves to get to the lip, traverse left. I probably would not want to fall from the top, since the hill is steep and there is a possibility of hitting the bloc below.

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start with both hands matched at the far right end of the undercling rail (pictured). Slap out right, using the fins to the right and a bomber kneebar to get holds high overhead, and then topout to the left. I would wear a kneepad or long pants

Location: Smedley Park > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Lay down start all the way to the left with the hands as indicated in the pictures. Climb a few fairly difficult moves into the start position of the regular Tardis Cave and finish the same way.

Location: Saul Preserve > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS on whatever holds you like, sometimes I start on the block to the right as well. There is a tree and ladder (hence the name) positioned above the boulder, which are fun to play around on.

Location: Saul Preserve > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start matched semi-far to the right. Use heel hooks to not dab while traversing slightly to the left, and then going up for the top out.

Location: Saul Preserve > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start low on two extremely sharp crimps. Pull hard for a difficult throw upwards onto better holds, then top out.

Location: R Crum Wall > Alligator Rock > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Stand start with large jug at chest height. Head straight up to an easy top out.

Location: R Crum Wall > Alligator Rock > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS with juggy arÃªte on far-right. Follow the arÃªte up. Large shelf on right near the top is off.Beta Video

Location: R Crum Wall > Alligator Rock > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS with juggy arÃªte on far-right. Follow the arÃªte up, only hand holds on the arÃªte are on. Large shelf on right near the top is off.Beta Video

Location: R Crum Wall > Alligator Rock > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS with juggy arÃªte on far-right. Move up and left to large edge. Traverse left then move up to the lip on sidepulls. Topping out there isnât really an option so drop or move left to finish over Cheap Thrills. The middle of this climb can be pretty wet after it rains.Beta Video

Location: R Crum Wall > Alligator Rock > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS with juggy arÃªte on far-right. Move up and left to large edge. Continue traversing left, staying low. Top out above jugs on the left. The middle of this climb can be pretty wet after it rains.Beta Video

Location: The Bulge > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Stand start on ledge in the dihedral at chest height. Move straight up and over the bulge. A fall from the top could be dicey.Beta Video

Location: The Bulge > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Stand start on ledge in the dihedral at chest height. Traverse left until you reach the left face of the bulge. Move left on small crimps to an easy top out.Beta Video

Location: The Bulge > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS on far-right side of the lip. Traverse left until you reach the left face of the bulge. Move straight up over the bulge on small crimps. This route originally began matched on a chest-height ledge in the dihedral.Beta Video

Location: Sunshine Boulders > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS on jugs, climb up the easy face.Beta Video

Location: Sunshine Boulders > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS with large jug in middle of face. Climb the face without using the arÃªte.Variation: SDS with large jug in middle of face, dyno to the lip.Beta Video

Location: Sunshine Boulders > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS with large jug in middle of face. Climb up the right side of the face.Beta Video

Location: Sunshine Boulders > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS on right side of face. Traverse left around the arÃªte to jugs on the left face.Beta Video

Location: Sunshine Boulders > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS matched low on the overhang. Traverse right to jugs, gain the lip and top out.Beta Video

Location: Sunshine Boulders > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS on far right of overhang. Traverse left as far as possible and top out.Beta Video

Location: Sunshine Boulders > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS and climb the left arÃªte. A fall on this route could be spicy, mind the chunks of quartz and try not to cheese grate.

Location: Sunshine Boulders > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS matched low on the arÃªte. Climb the arÃªte, avoiding the tree dab.V0 Variation: SDS with large jug in middle of face. Climb the face using the arÃªte.Beta Video

Route: Teeth Of Lions Rule The Divine
Location: Sunshine Boulders > Crum Woods > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: SDS in middle of face. Climb straight up without using either arÃªte. A fall on this route could be spicy, mind the chunks of quartz and try not to cheese grate.

Location: Tyler Park Bouldering > Southeastern Lowlands > Pennsylvania
Description: Start on the good jug on the left side of the main vertical crack. Move up and then all the way right to finish.
